<t font='PuristaBold'>Indiana University Informed Consent Statement for a Study on Human-Automation Interaction</t><br/><br/>

You are invited to participate in a study on Human-Automation Interaction. Please read this statement and ask any questions you may have before agreeing to participate in the study. The study is being conducted by Eric S. Vorm from the IU School of Informatics and Computing. The study is open to participants who meet the following criteria: 18 or older; proficient, fluent, or native ability in spoken and written English communication; visual impairment no worse than 20/40 with correction; agree to this informed consent statement.<br/><br/>

<t font='PuristaBold'>Study purpose</t><br/>
The purpose of this study is to explore how human workload level, situation awareness, and rate of utilization change with different degrees of automation. We are interested in learning more about how different types of automated functions can affect human performance. Possible outcomes of this research could help improve system designs using automation in domains such as aviation (manned and unmanned) and process control.<br/><br/>

<t font='PuristaBold'>Procedures for the study</t><br/>
If you agree to participate in this study, you will do the following things:<br/>
    1. Answer some questions about yourself, such as your experience in aviation training or flight simulators, and basic demographics like your birth year, gender, and so on.<br/>
    2. Take part in a simulation controlling multiple remotely piloted aircraft to help monitor for simulated forest fires. <br/>
    3. Answer questions during the simulation.<br/><br/>

<t font='PuristaBold'>Risks of taking part in the study</t><br/>
While we do not anticipate any risks from participating, you must stop participating and notify the principal investigator if at any time you feel your mental or physical well-being, personal values, or dignity is being harmed. There is also the possibility of loss of confidentiality.<br/><br/> PAGEBREAK1

<t font='PuristaBold'>Benefits of taking part in the study</t><br/>
The benefit of participation that is reasonable to expect is as follows: The data gathered may contribute to an understanding of human-automation interaction.<br/><br/>

<t font='PuristaBold'>Confidentiality</t><br/>
Your personal information will not be identified or shared or used for another purpose. Reported results will not contain information that may be used to identify you. SSL encryption protects the privacy of your Internet session. The web server is kept at a secure site behind a firewall.<br/><br/>

Efforts will be made to keep your personal information confidential. We cannot guarantee absolute confidentiality. Your personal information may be disclosed if required by law. Your identity will be held in confidence in reports in which the study may be published.<br/><br/>

Organizations that may inspect and/or copy your research records for quality assurance and data analysis include groups such as the study investigator and his/her research associates, the Indiana University Institutional Review Board or its designees, and (as allowed by law) state or federal agencies, specifically the Office for Human Research Protections (OHRP).<br/><br/>

<t font='PuristaBold'>Compensation</t><br/>
You will not be paid for participating.<br/><br/>

<t font='PuristaBold'>Contacts for questions or problems</t><br/>
